As of 2400 hours on February 4, at least 36 concentrated isolation points had been opened in Wuhan, according to incomplete statistics from southern weekend.

"according to the requirements, the community disinfects three or four times a day, but after each trip, the protective clothing can not be used. If this consumption continues, the protective clothing will soon be gone, " Ms. Zhou said. "So we have to not wear it. "

On the third day of his confinement, Chen Zhen's father was finally transferred to a community center hospital for treatment. "The only thing left to do is to trust the doctor. "

This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Du Siqi, southern weekend correspondent

Southern weekend intern, Ren Miaolin

Editor in chief | Wu Xiaoyu

On Feb. 3,2020, the 10th day of a recurring fever, Chen Zhen's father, a Wuhan native, was sent to a central quarantine site after she feared that a father diagnosed with pneumonia would infect other family members and "drag down" the entire family.

The central quarantine point was set up in an emergency converted hotel. A day ago, the Wuhan New Pneumonia Control and Prevention Headquarters issued circular No. 10, deciding that from the date of the circular, close contacts of fever patients diagnosed with pneumonia at fever clinics and pneumonia patients with COVID-19 infection (hereinafter referred to as "NCP") throughout the city were sent to the central isolation observation point by vehicle from each district.

The decree was transmitted from top to bottom, like ripples on a lake, from the Wuhan Municipal Government, to the district under its jurisdiction, quickly reaching the street level. At the end of the chain, the community is the last pressure valve.

Unbeknownst to Chen Zhen, for many community leaders at the end of the chain, the "order of ten" also came out of the blue. Southern weekend reporters learned that the first two days of centralized isolation, although there are quarantine points, but there is no clear method of isolation, there is no medical staff, also lack of medicine. As a result, the calls have snowballed back into the community.

In the 13 days since the city was sealed off, the same thing happened every day. The suffering of the patient, the anxiety of the family, and the pressure of the community go hand in hand. Patients seeking treatment on the road, and the collision and even conflict in the community, reflect the complexity of social governance at the grass-roots level.

Fortunately, a more detailed epidemic prevention mechanism has been activated, and social pressure has eased. As of 2400 hours on February 4, Wuhan had opened 132 concentrated isolation points, with 12,571 beds and 5,425 people under concentrated isolation, according to data released by Wuhan. Medical and life services are quietly catching up.

Before this, Wuhan Transforms Including International Convention and Exhibition Center, including three "shelter hospitals" , provides 3,800 beds, mainly receives the new coronary pneumonia the mild illness patient. On the morning of February 4, the completed Vulcan Mountain hospital admitted 50 patients who had been transferred.

Also on that day, Jiang Chaoliang, the party secretary of Hubei Province, went to Wuchang District to check the placement of suspected patients in the centralized isolation point, stressing the commitment to "receive all that we can, and treat all that we can" .

1
Mount up immediately

1

###Mount up immediately

"Order Ten" made a difference for Chen Zhen.

Chen Zhen's father, who had been diagnosed by doctors at Wuhan's Third Hospital as highly suspicious of new crown pneumonia, had been placed in isolation at home.

His father became ill on January 25, and Chen Zhen has been pounding on his bed ever since, but without a kit, he has not been able to confirm the diagnosis.

A diagnosis means a hospital admission number. And the father can only have a fever repeatedly at home: the chest is frowsty, lack of energy, breathing difficulty, all pester the pain that pesters new crown pneumonia patient also pesters him.

But it's not a complete quarantine. In order to get the medicine and get the effective diagnosis, they have to shuttle to and from the hospital and the residence in Wuhan every day.

In the experts, such suspected cases like "walking virus" , do not know which day will suddenly leave, do not know when people around will be "hit" .

On the afternoon of February 2, when Chen Zhen saw the order of ten, he immediately called the Poly Property community. She recalled that she was told by community workers that specialist treatment was available at the isolation point and that "I would feel more comfortable taking my father there. ".

Early on the morning of February 3, she drove her father to an isolation point about three kilometres from home.

The four-star, 16-story, 297-room hotel was cleared a day ago as a central quarantine zone for suspected new pneumonia patients.

In the hotel lobby, Chen Zhen was stopped, and the staff made it clear that "only suspected patients in quarantine can go upstairs. "

As Chen Zhen watched her father take his luggage upstairs, she was about to leave when an ambulance arrived at the hotel with a paramedic who told her it was to test the quarantined patient for nucleic acid.

Happy, Chen Zhen tweeted: Ten days into my father's fever, my father was sent to a central quarantine facility, and a doctor has been there to do a nucleic acid test, and I hope everything goes well.

However, the father was not tested and treated as quickly as expected.

That afternoon, her father was again struggling to breathe, and she borrowed a home oxygen machine to deliver it. Seeing that his father was not well, Chen Zhen took him to the hospital to line up for a nucleic acid test, and transfusion treatment.

Southern weekend reporters learned that this isolation point has seven or eight staff members, in addition to the delivery of rice and some basic medicine to the heat, the rest need patients to take care of themselves.

In a wechat group of more than 100 quarantined patients and their families, Chen Zhen was inundated with requests for medicines, tests, meal times and shots to go out almost all day.

They often wait for only three words: "until further notice. "

When it was nearly midnight on February 3, the staff finally informed the patients in the group to go to the first floor for nucleic acid testing.

Southern weekend reporters repeatedly contacted the hotel staff, the phone has not been answered. However, from the Qiao estuary a hotel staff to understand that the test out, the results of negative people can directly leave. Among the confirmed patients, mild cases continue to be quarantined in the hotel, while those with severe cases go to the hospital. But he did not know "who arranged the beds in the hospital" .

According to the Qiao estuary on Duty Room staff February 3 to southern weekend reporters said, the implementation of the isolation point can not be put in place, accommodation and treatment conditions will follow later.

2
Community "stewards"

2

###Community "stewards"

In the still-undefined epidemic situation, community cadres have become the most accessible "stewards" for citizens looking for help from here.

According to "order" requirements, the centralized treatment and isolation of the "four categories of personnel. They are: confirmed patients with new pneumonia, suspected patients, patients with undefined fever, close contacts of confirmed patients. Among them, patients with severe diagnosis must be admitted to designated hospitals, serious suspected patients must be admitted to hospital for treatment. Can Not be admitted to the hospital with mild diagnosis and suspected patients, must be concentrated isolation, can not be isolated at home.

However, at the community level, some communities have been given the task of isolating two categories of people.

So it was in a community in Hanyang District where Qin Qi was the party secretary. Qin Qi, she took the community 9 staff, 24-hour duty, responsible for 6 communities, a total of more than 5,000 people of the epidemic prevention and control. "there are now three confirmed cases, one in hospital and two in isolation at home. "

In a notice given to Qin Qi on February 2, they could organize community residents to go to a hotel for quarantine. "But only close contacts of highly suspected and confirmed patients can go. "

What is a high degree of suspicion? Qin Qi can only judge according to the situation and feeling. "such as a very bad cough, high fever does not drop, breathing difficulties. "

Combining southern weekend reporters'interviews with different communities, there are two paths that can be centrally segregated. One is the community to contact the initiative to ask if they would like to; the other is to apply to the community, but if the conditions do not meet will be rejected.

The Gao Xia who lives in a certain area of Qiao estuary is the community contact actively. She often lived in Xiaogan, January 13, her husband began repeated fever, she came to Wuhan.

Gao told southern weekly on Feb. 3 that more than 10 days after coming to Wuhan, her husband was diagnosed with new pneumonia and died hastily on Jan. 31. No decent packing, no family to say goodbye, and all she got was a cremation bill.

Before the pain of losing her husband could be digested, Gaoxia and her son began to have fever.

There were no beds in the hospital, and a friend in Wuhan took in the mother and son in isolation. "My son goes to Tongji Hospital, huake affiliated hospital, to get six to seven vials a day, " she said, mostly by taking pills to relieve symptoms.

At noon on February 2, Gao Xia received a phone call from the community cadres, asking her to take the necessities of life. In the afternoon, a car picked them up and sent them to the hotel, which is 6 kilometers away.

Ben was living under someone else's fence. Gaoxia decided to go with her son. Gaoxia and her son encountered a similar situation to Chen Zhen's father, and could not come out again after going in. "What about my child's daily intravenous drip? "

In this 13 jurisdictions, a total area of 8,569.15 square kilometers of the mega-city, Gaoxia did not know where to go. She could no longer help herself. She burst into tears on the phone and hung up with the southern weekend reporter.

By the time they reconnected the next day, they had been moved to another quarantine point.

3
Pressure, authority, and change

3

###Pressure, authority, and change

As the first line of defense for epidemic prevention and control, the community also stands at the forefront of risks and contradictions.

On the morning of February 2, Cheng Hua, a community secretary on Hanyang District's Jiangdi Street, found the sudden arrival of the order "comforting" .

In Cheng Hua's view, the policy of centralized segregation was originally intended to share the pressure of the community and reduce the risk of segregation at home. Previously, he wore a daily general medical mask, wearing a disposable protective clothing, and home isolation of the confirmed, suspected patients. "We are also worried about being infected and passing it on to other residents and relatives. "

Relief quickly turned to work pressure, as policy implementation depended on them, as it had 11 days earlier.

It was the early hours of January 23, when Wuhan decided to "close the city" to contain the spread of the epidemic. In the darkness, the news quickly reached the community.

At the same time, there is the command from the "order seven. ". "Order Seven" clear: the city's communities to fully investigate the district served by the fever patients. For those patients who need to go to the fever clinic, each district will arrange to send a vehicle to the designated fever clinic for consultation. For those patients who do not need to go to the follow-up clinic for consultation, the communities will carry out home observation, and the communities will do a good job in providing home observation services to the citizens.

"It happened so fast that everyone, everything and everything rushed to the community, " Zhou Hui, a community secretary on Erqiao street in Jianghan, Hanyang District, recalled to reporters at southern weekend on February 4. She hasn't stopped since January 24th.

Compared to several other communities in Jianghan Erqiao Street, the epidemic in Zhou Hui's neighborhood is not serious. There are no confirmed cases in the entire community, and there are five suspected cases. But with more than 7,000 people in the community and many retirees, she worries that in a severe epidemic, the elderly will become a target of the virus.

On the first day of the siege, Zhou and her 15 colleagues took no precautions. On January 26th street offices began handing out disposable masks. The next day, they were given some disinfectant and 100 protective clothing.

In addition to community cadres, grid players play an important role in China's grass-roots governance system.

According to the number of grid workers published in Wuhan in 2019, there were more than 16,000 full-time and part-time grid workers in the past year, according to the standard of about 300-500 households or 1,000 residents. By this calculation, Zhou's community has at least seven grid members.

Community cadres and grid members have been mobilized to work round the clock. 24 hours, they keep getting calls.

Most of them are complaint calls. As soon as the telephone is picked up, it is often like a barrage of questions: Why not go to the Hospital of the car? Why isn't there a bed? Why hasn't there been a quarantine?

What Zhou Hui can do is to pick up a pen, write it down and report it. Unlike A top-down command, however, a bottom-up response, no one knows if it will stop at any point.

This conversation is repeated every day.

On the other end of the line were anxious residents. "You keep talking about reflection, but when does it stop? "

On the other end of the line was a frazzled staff member, "we reported from start to finish. "

Community workers and residents are exhausted, but the bickering and complaining continues unabated. Both Start and end points point to the same problem, a shortage of resources.

According to several community secretaries interviewed by southern weekend, they are willing to do things, but the reality is that community resources can not keep up.

Take, for example, order 10. According to government documents, coercive measures can be taken against people who do not want to be quarantined, but only community police can enforce them. "We don't have the authority, we can only go to the docking, but it will take time, " a community secretary on Erqiao street in Jianghan, Hanyang District, told southern weekend.

In his view, the current residents of the most urgent demand is the bed. Having a bed means that the patient is in professional isolation, thereby cutting off the source of infection. The shortage of beds and demands for treatment have left patients and their families searching for any piece of information.

As of February 4,8,254 beds had been opened in 28 designated hospitals in Wuhan and 8,182 had been used. On the same day, the National Health Commission said it was mobilizing medical staff and nurses from all over the country to take care of patients in Wuhan. At the same time, Wuhan's Lei Shen Shan Hospital, which will provide 1,600 beds for patients, is expected to be delivered on February 5. Only confirmed patients will be admitted to the two hospitals.

On the night of February 4, Chen Zhen received another piece of good news and another piece of bad news.

The bad news is, the father's nucleic acid test came back, positive for the first time. The good news is that quarantine workers are beginning to count test results on wechat groups, saying they are referring some of the patients who test positive to hospital.

On Feb. 5, the third day of his confinement, Chen Zhen's father was finally transferred to a community center hospital for treatment. It wasn't a big hospital, but there were beds and hospitals, and Chen Zhen was relieved. "The only thing left to do is to trust the doctor. "

(the names given in the article are pseudonyms at the request of the interviewee)
